Suwannee Pineview Elementary
September 10 at 8:58 AM ·

On Tuesday, Mrs. White combined her Math and Science lessons. She gave her students a specific amount of "money" to "buy" their materials. Her Fourth Grade students used their engineering skills to design and build a structure to hold a raw egg. The structure was not only for holding the egg, but for keeping the egg from cracking when it was dropped from a height above their heads. Afterward, Mrs. White took her students outside to test out their inventions. Pictured in the group photos are students whose eggs survived the drop!

shared_text:
Suwannee Pineview Elementary
September 9 at 9:04 AM ·

Mrs. Pennington’s first graders conducted an experiment to observe raisins “dancing” in soda! They began by making a prediction about what they thought might happen when they added raisins to a container of ginger ale. Students were excited to see the reaction caused by the bubbles in the soda. To extend the activity, students added raisins to a container of water and saw that no reaction happened. Afterward, students illustrated their observations in their STEM journal. Thank you to Mrs. Amy Lang for donating the clear plastic containers used for the demonstration.

Suwannee Middle School: Official SCSB Site
September 3 at 2:07 PM ·

Beginning Tuesday, Sept. 8th, we will no longer be giving out warnings for violation of dress code and electronic devices. If you are caught in violation of either of these, you will be given a referral and there will be consequences.

• No holes in clothes without patches or leggings underneath...no skin should be visible. Dresses, shorts, skirts should be no shorter than 4 inches above the knee. No bedroom slippers or pajamas should be worn at any time.

• Cell phones/electronic devices should only be out before school, during lunch and after school....not in between classes or on the way to and from lunch.

• When using electronic devices, only one earbud should be in your ear and that is for your safety.

September 1 at 9:11 AM ·

Students (Pre-K through Fifth Grade) at Suwannee Pineview Elementary are learning a new science word every week, ranging from comet to vertebrate. Each week, our students will learn the word by creating a student-friendly definition, using the word in a sentence, drawing a picture, and looking for the word in their daily surroundings. The Science Word of the Week is displayed in each of our classrooms, along with the Media Center and in our Front Lobby. You may also look for our Science Word of the Week on our marquee, our Facebook page, and our school's website. We are very excited about expanding our scientific vocabulary! Below is this week's word (Condensation), which is displayed on one of the bulletin boards in our Front Lobby.

shared_text:
Suwannee Pineview Elementary
August 27 at 10:58 AM ·

"Last week, we incorporated social/emotional learning (SEL) with STEM concepts. We read, "Have You Filled a Bucket Today?," by Carol McCloud. Then we discussed how to be “bucket fillers” and not “bucket dippers.” This means we make others feel better by doing and saying kind things. Next, we designed and created our own buckets, and tested their strength by filling them with pennies. The only materials students could use were scissors, construction paper, a chenille stem (pipe cleaner), and up to 12 inches of tape. Now, our display will help to remind us to show kindness all year, AND we got firsthand experience in the importance of planning a design before building!" ~Mrs. Kristy Chauncey, Third Grade Teacher at SPE

shared_text:
Suwannee Pineview Elementary
August 9 at 5:09 PM ·

We are so excited to meet our students tomorrow!! We have worked extremely hard to prepare the school for your safe return. We have new arrival and dismissal procedures to follow to ensure the safety of all. Thank you for your cooperation.

* Parents will not be able to walk students to class. We will have many staff members in the drop-off areas, lobby, and hallways to ensure students are happy and delivered to their classroom.

*Parents must stay in their vehicles during drop-off and pick-up. We ask that you not walk up to the school at dismissal to pick up your child.

* The 21st Century After School program will NOT begin tomorrow. It starts on Monday,Aug. 17. If you filled out an application, you should be getting a phone call this week.

Bell Schedule:
First Bell- 7:50 am
Tardy Bell-7:55 am
Bus Dismissal-2:35 pm
Pick-up Dismissal- 2:40 pm

Thank you so much for a great start! We are looking forward to seeing our students tomorrow and to a great year at Suwannee Pineview Elementary!

post_text:
When school starts in August, there will be four models for parents to consider:

• Traditional Public Education - 5 days per week - face to face - "regular school"
• Temporary HYBRID Learning Model - 1 day per week consultation at the school site - digital curriculum supported by parents and an assigned Learning Coach
• Suwannee Virtual School - same virtual school model that has been offered for the past several years in Suwannee County
• Home Education - same program that has been available - parents control content and supply materials - only requirement is annual evaluation per Florida Statute.

Please visit the link below to view important information regarding the SCSD reopening plan and to register your child for the option that is best suited for your family.

http://www.suwannee.k12.fl.us/scsd-reopening-plan

RIVEROAK Technical College
June 23 at 11:39 AM ·

RIVEROAK Technical College (RTC) will be closing campus for approximately two weeks and plans to re-open on Monday, July 6, 2020, however, return date is subject to change.

RTC will use this time to do a thorough deep cleaning of campus before reopening. RTC will continue to offer GED testing on Wednesdays, beginning at 8:00 a.m. Testers are encouraged to bring their own mask to wear while on campus but if the tester does not have a mask, RTC will provide one. Please note, upon arrival to campus, testers will have their temperature checked before entering campus. No one with a temperature above 100 degrees will be allowed on campus. For further questions and information, contact RTC at (386) 647-4200 or reach out to us via Facebook Messenger.

#GrowYourFutureWithUs

RIVEROAK Technical College is a recipient of Coronavirus Aid, Relief, & Economic Security (CARES) Act funding.

Under the CARES Act, all schools that participate in the federal student aid programs have been allocated funds to make emergency grants to students who meet the requirements to receive federal student financial aid for expenses related to the disruption of campus operations due to Coronavirus (COVID-19).

This week we have been issuing relief checks to all our adult postsecondary students in an effort to supply financial assistance during this difficult time.

#Letnothingdimyourfuture #GrowWithUs #GrowYourFutureWithUs #wearefamily

May 11 at 11:23 AM ·

RIVEROAK is accepting applications for the Electricity Program!

The Electricity Program prepares students for employment as electrician helpers, as well as, residential and commercial electricians. Classroom instruction and practical laboratory applications teach students the correct installation and maintenance of electrical wiring and equipment involving motors, motor controls, and power and lighting systems in residential, commercial, and industrial applications.

#GrowYourFutureWithUs

RIVEROAK Technical College
April 8 at 1:47 PM ·

CareerSource North Florida News!

Re-employment Applications may now be downloaded and printed from CareerSource's website at https://careersourcenorthflorida.com/reemployment-assistance/.

***Printed Re-employment Applications, along with envelopes, are available at RIVEROAK Technical College's front entrance. You may pick up a printed application Monday thru Wednesday, from 8:00 a.m. to 4:15 p.m.

As we continue to telework, we can still be reached at 850-973-9675 or at contact@careersourcenorthflorida.com.

Also, anyone with time on their hands may want to use this time to learn and grow. We have developed Skill Up North Florida (http://northflorida.skillupamerica.org/), a skill-building system with modules of micro-training. Also, we are offering Rise Up online, a National Retail Federation training in retail and customer service. Rise Up is a Nationally recognized credential in the retail industry. Register @ https://careersourcenorthflorida.formstack.com/forms/riseup

Suwannee County Schools: Official SCSB Site added 128 new photos — with Danielle Deanna Warrlock.
February 28 at 2:03 PM ·

On Wednesday, February 26th, Suwannee High School and Branford High School attended the Northwest Florida Construction Career Day in Jacksonville, Florida.

In total, close to 300 students represented Suwannee County at the Career Day. While at the Career Day, students visited multiple hands on learning labs where they were able to complete projects or partake in activities to learn about the day-to-day life in the many careers available.

Students learned that many of these jobs pay well above minimum wage, provide benefits, pensions, and required a High School diploma and a willingness to learn and work. Students had the opportunity to speak with possible employers and take home information about apprentice and internship programs in Northeast Florida, some even as close as Lake City.

The Suwannee County School District, my choice for high quality education!

The Suwannee County School Board Meeting was held at Branford High School this evening. The meeting began with student remarks and pledge to the flag by BES students.

Special recognition by the Superintendent went to Isabella Hobday from Branford Elementary School for winning the Suwannee County School District Spelling Bee and to Dusty Wardrep from Suwannee Middle School for being the runner up. The Superintendent also recognized Branford High School student Barrett Young for being Branford High School’s Sunshine State Scholar.

Both of our Student Ambassadors, Barrett Young (BHS) and Antonio White (SHS), sat with the board and added their input into tonight’s agenda.

Awesome job by these students and keep up the great work! We are so proud of these students and how they represent our county!

The Suwannee County School District, my choice for high quality education!

Career and Technical Education Month, or CTE Month, is a public awareness campaign that takes place each February to celebrate the value of CTE and the achievements and accomplishments of CTE programs across the country.

• Suwannee Riverside Elementary: School of the Arts

post_text:
During the entire 2017-2018 fiscal year (July ‘17-June ‘18), the Suwannee County schools were entirely fluorescent with ballast operation. In June of 2018, the SCSD Facilities Department started the LED change-out, which involved removing the ballast and fluorescent tube, rewiring the fixture and replacing them with a new LED tube. The SCSD now has an entire year of data with the LED lights in place.
The data in the photo is actual billing data. This is the cumulative monthly electric bills for ALL facilities. You can see the decrease in every month compared to the previous years billing. The electric bills encompass much more than just lighting, all the equipment like HVAC and cafe' etc. are also included.
In total, the SCSD saved $139,748 in just ONE year due to the LED lights!
The Suwannee County School District, my choice for high quality education!

The Suwannee County School District Board Meeting began with SPS kindergartens and first graders saying the pledge and singing a song!

**Levi Bass

**James King.
Please congratulate them when you see them.

The Art Department at Suwannee High School has been chosen to represent Florida in this year's National Christmas Tree display on the Ellipse in President’s Park. Handcrafted ornaments will adorn 56 smaller trees that surround the National Christmas Tree. The 56 trees represent each U.S. state, territory and the District of Columbia as part of the America Celebrates display. Mrs. Pam Williams, Art Teacher at SHS, said "It is such an incredible honor to be able to represent our state in this fashion. We have so many creative students at SHS; it is nice to be recognized for our talents." #BulldogPride

Become a Guardian ad Litem Volunteer!

Guardian ad Litem volunteers stand up for the best interests of abused, abandoned or neglected children. Appointed by judges, they speak up for the child’s needs in the courtroom and the community.

They ensure that the child is safe, protected and provided with a stable home.

For more information, please contact Leslie Nestic at (386) 758-1170.

Suwannee High School and Suwannee Middle School held their annual FFA Fall Round Up on October 24, 2019 at the SHS Land Lab.

The Round Up concluded with a cake auction. According to SHS FFA Advisor Travis Tuten, $7,465 was raised off the cake auction.

The Suwannee County School District, my choice for high quality education!

post_text:
On October 22, 2019 the Branford High School FFA Land Lab was officially named the “Willie Veal Land Lab” in honor of Willie Veal. Mr. Veal taught agriculture at BHS and was very influential to the FFA program. Veal previously received the Florida FFA Honorary Member, which is the highest award one can receive at the state level. BHS FFA President Barrett Young says, “Thank you Mr. Veal for your continued service to Branford FFA and for being a role model to young members and advisors everywhere.”

Young was not the only one to praise Veal for his time and effort to Branford FFA. District 1 Board Member Jerry Taylor said, “Mr. Veal gave his life to the school and the students.”

The Suwannee County School District, my choice for high quality education!

RIVEROAK Technical College
October 18, 2019 at 1:25 PM ·

Both the Auto Collision Technology Technician and Auto Service Technology I Programs are accepting applications for Spring Term!

Automotive Collision Technology Technician prepares students for employment as automobile body repairers, painters, repairer helpers, and painter helpers.

Automotive Service Technology I prepares students for careers in the automotive industry. Using diagnostic and test equipment, students will learn operational theory, diagnostic procedures, and industry accepted methods of service and repair of currently automotive systems.

Both programs are accredited by the National Automotive Technicians Education Foundation (NATEF) and offers Automotive Service Excellence (ASE) certifications.

For more information about these programs please contact RTC at (386) 647-4210!

#GrowYourFutureWithUs

shared_text:
Suwannee Riverside Elementary
October 9, 2019 at 8:12 PM ·

Captain Chip Leathlean, of Suwannee County Fire & Rescue, went out of his way for our sweet Jakhyriana. When the Captain noticed she was not engaged in the fire safety presentation like the other children, he took it upon himself to help her really see by touching things. He kindly pulled her aside to let her hold and touch part of the hose. Her face lit up! It made her day and I am sure it made his, too.

So thankful for our First Responders and their loyalty and commitment to our community.

#CaptainLeathleanisahero

Jakhyriana’s mom gave us permission to post this.
